    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_507358">I would buy that as a plausible theory!<br />
<br />
Personally I have 4 base passwords: <br />
1 - don't care about <br />
2 - ok i made this one semi secure <br />
3 - bank level password<br />
4 - password vault password (used one place, is all messed up, no common words, craziness, over 30 characters long)<br />
<br />
I say base because they are based around a root and then modified for different sites.<br />
<br />
I'll give an example of my thought process on creating passwords. Lets say I'm creating a password for Amazon and I know I'm having taco's for dinner. I might use the phrase &quot;I hate heartburn&quot;. I would then turn that into Ih8&lt;3burn! That would be strong enough for most but then I would want to specify it for Amazon, I would take a number I like and use it, say PI - 3.14 I would then take the 3rd, 1st and 4th letter of Amazon (a, A, z) and work them into my password using another 3 digit number like 271, i would then insert the letters in their place Izha8&lt;3buArn! (Safehouse would be Iehf8&lt;3buSrn!, excluding the obviously) <br />
<br />
When I first started this I would type out Ih8&lt;3burn! write down the important letters for the Site I was at, put them in the correct order and arrow over to insert them. Now I just know the stupid passwords.<br />
<br />
As long as you remember your &quot;phrase&quot; and your favorite number formulas it is pretty easy to remember. For the numbers you can use stuff that means stuff to you, like birthdays, anniversaries and such, so long as you remember the &quot;formulas&quot;.<br />
<br />
All that being said, I've actually used password for a password before... and my current I don't give a crap password isn't much better. This works for me it may not work for you, but it is best to come up with something that is not to obvious in case one does get stolen.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
